            <drawer-more
              slot="review"
              max-lines="3"
              status="closed"
            >
              <span slot="content">Rating: 8/10 ⭐️

I expected a fun tournament, but the dark shift into a thriller totally blew me away.

What Worked:
60-foot tank gives the underwater scenes a terrifying, tactile weight. Through my Faith Methodism lens, seeing Harry risk his lead to save a competitor’s sister reminds me that true grace prioritizes others over glory. Fiennes presence and Doyle’s darker score perfectly anchor the dangerous climax.

The Cuts:
The opening act really dragged for me; skipping the Quidditch match makes the campsite attack feel abrupt. Keeping it spoiler-free, Dumbledore aggressively manhandling Harry feels wildly out of character and awkward. Plus, condensing a 600-page book sidelines the day-to-day magic, leaving the trio’s usual sleuthing no room to breathe.

Verdict:
A stunning, high-stakes turning point. Perfect for intense thrills, but skip if you want cozy magic.

Favorite Line: “Dark and difficult times lie ahead.”</span>
            </drawer-more>
